          "body": "Naaman's confession in verse 15 is among the most remarkable in the Old Testament: 'Now I know that there is no God in all the earth, but in Israel.' This is not cautious theological hedging; it is a monotheistic declaration from a Syrian soldier who came to buy a cure and received a conversion. He offers his wealth again, and again Elisha refuses — with an oath. The prophet's refusal is not mere personal modesty; it guards the integrity of the grace. If Naaman can pay for the healing, the healing becomes a transaction, God becomes a contractor, and the prophet becomes a vendor. Elisha will not allow it. Naaman then requests two mule-loads of Israelite earth — because he has concluded that YHWH's worship requires Israelite soil. This reflects ancient Near Eastern theology in which gods were territorial, and Naaman is working out his new monotheism with the conceptual tools available to him. Calvin (commentary on 2 Kings) notes this with pastoral charity: new converts often carry residual theological frameworks into their early faith. Then comes the Rimmon petition (5:18) — perhaps the most pastorally searching moment of the chapter. Naaman knows he will have to accompany the king of Aram into the temple of Rimmon, and that physically bowing while supporting the king's arm will look like worship. He asks for pre-emptive pardon, twice. Elisha's response — 'Go in peace' — does not answer the theological puzzle directly. The commentators divide: Calvin reads it as dismissal, not absolution; others (Peter Craigie, Iain Provan) read it as pastoral permission for a conscientious convert in a genuinely impossible situation. What is clear is that Elisha does not demand immediate resolution of every theological complexity before sending Naaman home. Grace in this chapter is patient with the newly converted."
