        "excerpt": "The LORD had given victory to Aram. The man was also a valiant warrior, but he was a leper.",
        "body": "The narrator's opening statement is theologically explosive and deliberately placed first: 'by him the LORD had given victory to Aram' (5:1). Before Naaman knows the LORD, before he asks anything of Israel's God, before the captive girl speaks, before any story begins — YHWH has already used him. Grace, in 2 Kings 5, does not wait for the recipient's faith. It precedes it, works through unlikely instruments (an enemy general), and sets the stage for its own disclosure. This is not universalism; it is a declaration of divine freedom. The same God who chose Israel chose to act through Naaman's military victories even while Naaman worshipped Rimmon.\n\nThe captive girl (5:2-3) functions as the human instrument of this preceding grace. She has every reason to be silent — she is a victim of Aramean aggression, a slave in the household of the general whose army took her. Her speech is not explained by the narrator; there is no account of her motives, her theology, or her inner struggle. She simply speaks the word she knows: there is a prophet in Samaria who can cure him. Calvin noted (in his sermons on 2 Kings) that God often uses those we would least expect — the powerless, the dispossessed — as the first voices of His grace. The girl's testimony sets in motion a chain of events that passes through royal miscommunication, prophetic intervention, and personal humiliation before it arrives at the Jordan.\n\nThe irony of Naaman's preparation for the journey (5:5) is sharp: ten talents of silver, six thousand shekels of gold, ten changes of clothes. This is a fortune — a king's ransom, literally. He is preparing to purchase his healing. The narrator does not editorialize; he simply records the inventory. But the inventory will become the chapter's sustained ironic theme: the wealth Naaman brings cannot buy what he needs, and the wealth Elisha refuses will reappear in Gehazi's hands as the instrument of judgment.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Tsaraat* (leprosy) in the Hebrew Bible is a broader category than modern Hansen's disease — it includes various skin conditions rendering the sufferer ritually unclean (Leviticus 13-14). The condition was socially devastating regardless of its exact medical identity. *Gibbor chayil* (valiant warrior, literally 'mighty man of valor') is the same phrase used of Boaz (Ruth 2:1) and Gideon (Judges 6:12) — the highest designation for a warrior. The tension of the verse is embedded in the vocabulary: maximum human honor + maximum human disqualification."
