        "body": "The royal letter scene (5:5-8) is a study in category error. The king of Aram assumes that healing, like diplomacy, can be transacted between kings. He writes a letter to the king of Israel: 'I have sent Naaman my servant to you, that you may cure him of his leprosy' (5:6). The king of Israel's response is not political calculation; it is genuine theological panic. He tears his clothes and says the theologically correct thing: 'Am I God, to kill and to make alive?' (5:7). The king of Israel knows, at the cognitive level, that he cannot do this. What he does not know — and what Elisha's intervention supplies — is that there is Someone in Israel who mediates the One who can.\n\nElisha's response in verse 8 is pastoral and corrective simultaneously: 'Why have you torn your clothes? Now let him come to me, and he shall know that there is a prophet in Israel.' The prophet rebukes the king's despair and restores the proper order: healing belongs to YHWH; it is mediated through His prophet; the prophet is in Israel. The purpose of the healing is stated here before it happens: 'he shall know that there is a prophet in Israel.' The miracle is not primarily therapeutic; it is doxological and epistemological. It will produce knowledge — specifically, knowledge of the prophetic office and through it, of the God who stands behind it.\n\nThe Deuteronomistic History consistently places the prophet above the king as the true mediator of divine will. The king represents political power; the prophet represents prophetic authority. In the northern kingdom, where the Omride dynasty has so thoroughly entangled the throne with Baal worship (1 Kings 16:29-33; 18:18-19), the king's helplessness before Naaman's request is almost symbolic: the palace has forfeited its capacity to point anyone to YHWH. The prophet's house must do what the palace cannot.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Navi* (prophet) appears at 5:3, 8, 13, and 22 — four times, forming an inclusio that marks prophetic authority as the chapter's structural spine. The prophet's house (*bet*) in 5:9 is the destination of horses, chariots, and military pageantry — military hardware at a domestic prophetic threshold, which is the chapter's architecture of reversal made visible."
