        "excerpt": "As the LORD lives, before whom I stand, I will take nothing... Go in peace.",
        "body": "Elisha's refusal of Naaman's gift (5:16) is more than personal modesty. It is a theological statement about the character of grace: what God gives freely cannot be sold. The oath formula — 'As the LORD lives, before whom I stand' — is the highest form of swearing available in ancient Israelite culture. Elisha is not saying 'I personally don't want it'; he is saying 'in the presence of the living God, before whom I serve, I will not monetize what He has done.' The prophet's authority is not available for purchase. The miracle's integrity depends on its remaining a gift. Paul articulates the same principle in 1 Corinthians 9:18 when he refuses payment for the gospel, lest he compromise its freedom. The chapter anticipates the apostolic pattern.\n\nThe Rimmon petition (5:17-18) is one of the most pastorally complex passages in the Old Testament. Naaman, a genuine convert, asks first for Israelite earth — a request rooted in ancient Near Eastern territorial theology, reflecting his limited understanding of YHWH's omnipresence. More theologically demanding is his double petition for pardon (5:18): he knows that his political role as the king of Aram's personal aide will require him to accompany his master into the temple of Rimmon, and that physically supporting the king as he bows will make Naaman appear to be bowing in pagan worship. He asks the LORD to pardon him 'in this matter' — twice, with the repetition emphasizing the weight of his concern.\n\nElisha's response — 'Go in peace' (5:19) — has generated significant commentary debate. Calvin (Institutes, III.19) treated it as a dismissal; he argued that Elisha did not actually address or approve the Rimmon situation, but sent Naaman away with a general benediction. Iain Provan (NICOT, 1 and 2 Kings) and others read it as pastoral accommodation to a genuine convert in an impossible situation — the same pastoral sensitivity Jesus shows in not demanding immediate resolution of every theological complexity from new converts. The text does not explicitly resolve the question, which may itself be the point: the narrator preserves the theological ambiguity, leaving the reader to reckon with the fact that genuine faith sometimes begins in conditions that cannot be made immediately tidy. What is unambiguous is that Naaman does not return to the LORD having resolved his problem; he returns having named it, asked for forgiveness, and been sent in peace.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Salach* (forgive/pardon, 5:18) — in the entire Hebrew Bible, YHWH is always the subject of *salach*; no human being ever forgives using this verb. By choosing it, Naaman is petitioning God directly, in the name and categories of Israel's covenant, even before he has left the prophet's presence. *Shalom* (peace, 5:19) — the same word Gehazi immediately weaponizes in 5:21-22, making the juxtaposition stark."
